<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-05-01T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-05-01T08:00:00-05:00" n="574" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d574">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">761.93/1770: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-01T20:00:00+07:00">May 1, 1944—8
                                p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received May 2—6: 57 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>753. Consul [at] Tihwa in telegram April 27 reports information from Foreign
                        Affairs Delegate as follows (Embassy’s 631, April 11, and 669, April
                        17):</p>
                    <p>Force of 1,000 Kazaks with machine guns and trench mortars have been
                        besieging Fuwen since morning April 26. Reinforcements being sent to relieve
                        besieged.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>